comments.body:
> And this pattern really confuses static analysis tools.

@furszy asked me offline to provide an example of such a tool in use.

Let's take [IWYU](https://include-what-you-use.org/) as an example and run it as follows:
```
cmake -B build -DCMAKE_C_COMPILER=clang-19 -DCMAKE_C_INCLUDE_WHAT_YOU_USE=include-what-you-use
cmake --build build -t tests
```

When run on the [branch](https://github.com/bitcoin-core/secp256k1/pull/1734#discussion_r2340384653) with a separate TU, it correctly identifies a [missing](https://github.com/bitcoin-core/secp256k1/pull/1734#discussion_r2340169815) header:
```
[ 60%] Building C object src/CMakeFiles/unit_test.dir/unit_test.c.o
Warning: include-what-you-use reported diagnostics:

(/home/hebasto/dev/secp256k1/secp256k1/src/unit_test.h has correct #includes/fwd-decls)

/home/hebasto/dev/secp256k1/secp256k1/src/unit_test.c should add these lines:
#include <stdint.h>         // for int64_t

/home/hebasto/dev/secp256k1/secp256k1/src/unit_test.c should remove these lines:

The full include-list for /home/hebasto/dev/secp256k1/secp256k1/src/unit_test.c:
#include "unit_test.h"
#include <stdint.h>         // for int64_t
#include <stdio.h>          // for fprintf, printf, NULL, stderr, perror
#include <stdlib.h>         // for EXIT_FAILURE, strtol, EXIT_SUCCESS, getenv
#include <string.h>         // for strcmp, strchr, strlen
#include <sys/types.h>      // for pid_t
#include <sys/wait.h>       // for waitpid
#include <unistd.h>         // for close, _exit, fork, pipe, read, write
#include "testrand_impl.h"  // for testrand_init
#include "tests_common.h"   // for gettime_i64
---
```

On this branch, `unit_test.c` is skipped during analysis (and I assume the same would happen with other tools).

